Silicon carbide (SiC) power-switching and radio-frequency semiconductor devices reached the stage of aggressive commercialization. Of all SiC devices, bipolar junction transistor (BJT) has the most far-reaching expectations with respect to many advantages of its material and device technology. Simultaneously, SiC BJT is far ahead of other SiC devices in terms of unfulfilled promises and frustrations experienced by device and process engineers. The problems involve challenging fundamental issues of SiC materials science.

The goal of the project was to explore novel ways of addressing one of the fundamental problems preventing commercialization of silicon carbide bipolar junction transistor &ndash; recombination-induced stacking fault generation in the BJT base leading to degradation of minority carrier lifetime and transistor gain. The investigated approach was based on a novel fabrication process that utilizes low-temperature selective epitaxial growth (LTSEG) replacing ion implantation when fabricating critical regions of the SiC transistor.

There were six significant outcomes from this project:

1)      The possibility of growing SiC at temperature significantly lower than the regular growth temperatures was explored and the viability of the technique has been demonstrated;

2)      Prototypes of SiC devices fabricated using the low-temperature epitaxial growth technique were demonstrated;

3)      The development of the selective growth technique was advanced to the level enabling fabrication of a number of useful device regions;

4)      Advantages and disadvantages of different masking materials as commercially-feasible mask-candidates for LTSEG were evaluated;

5)      Promising ways of conducting self-aligned fabrication compatible with LTSEG were identified;

6)      BJT design issues benefiting from the fabrication of the critical device regions by the BJT technique were investigated by computer modeling and device fabrication.

